ğŸ”¹ Polymorphism â€“ Detailed Explanation

Polymorphism is an OOPS concept where one entity can have multiple forms.
The word polymorphism comes from:

Poly â†’ many

Morphism â†’ forms

In object-oriented programming, polymorphism allows the same method name to behave differently based on the object or the context in which it is used.

ğŸ”¹ Real-Life Example of Polymorphism

A common real-life example is the word â€œdriveâ€:

A person drives a car

A person drives a bike

A person drives a truck

The action is the same (drive), but the behavior is different depending on the vehicle.

Similarly, in programming, the same method can perform different actions depending on the object calling it.

ğŸ”¹ Why Polymorphism Is Used

Polymorphism is used to:

Increase flexibility

Improve code reusability

Reduce complexity

Make code easier to extend and maintain

It allows us to write general code that works for different objects.

ğŸ”¹ Types of Polymorphism
1ï¸âƒ£ Compile-Time Polymorphism (Static Polymorphism)

Compile-time polymorphism occurs when the method call is resolved at compile time.

This is achieved using method overloading.

Explanation:

Same method name

Different number or type of parameters

Real-Life Example:

A calculator can add two numbers or three numbers.
The operation is the same, but inputs differ.

2ï¸âƒ£ Run-Time Polymorphism (Dynamic Polymorphism)

Run-time polymorphism occurs when the method call is resolved at runtime.

This is achieved using method overriding.

Explanation:

Same method name

Same parameters

Different implementation in child class

Real-Life Example:

A Shape class has a method draw().
A Circle draws differently than a Rectangle, even though both use draw().

ğŸ”¹ Key Difference Between Compile-Time and Run-Time Polymorphism
Compile-Time	Run-Time
Method Overloading	Method Overriding
Resolved at compile time	Resolved at runtime
Faster	More flexible
No inheritance required	Inheritance required
ğŸ”¹ One-Line Closing (Strong)

Polymorphism allows the same method to perform different actions based on the object, making the code flexible and extensible.

